imp_p <- ggplot(df19, aes(y=Imp, x = TYPE)) + geom_boxplot() + 
  stat_summary(fun.y=mean, colour="black", geom="point", shape=8,
               size=3,show_guide = FALSE, position=position_dodge(width=0.75)) + 
  ylab("Impervious surface (%)") + xlab("") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust=1, vjust=1))

scale_p <- ggplot(df19, aes(y=gloom, x = TYPE)) + geom_boxplot() + 
  stat_summary(fun.y=mean, colour="black", geom="point", shape=8,
               size=3,show_guide = FALSE, position=position_dodge(width=0.75)) +
  ylab("gloomy scale density (log10[x+1]) per 15cm") + xlab("") + ylim(0,2.5) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, hjust=1, vjust=1))
cowplot::plot_grid(imp_p, scale_p)

2 Scale ‘Diversity’

2.1 Scale Richness

Richness 2018 vs 2020 (per tree). * = mean 

df_r <- df %>% mutate(Richness = rowSums(.[,8:12]!=0))

ggplot(df_r, aes(y=Richness, x = TYPE)) + geom_boxplot() + 
  stat_summary(fun.y=mean, colour="black", geom="point", shape=8,
               size=3,show_guide = FALSE, position=position_dodge(width=0.75)) + 
  ylab("Scale richness") + xlab("") + facet_grid(~YEAR)

2.2 Scale loading proportions

Mean Propotions of each scale species per red maple type by year.

B = obscure, G = gloomy, J = Japanese maple, L = lecanium/soft, O = oyster, X = unidentified 

dff1 <- df %>% group_by(YEAR, TYPE) %>% 
  summarise_each(funs(mean), G15, B15, O15, J15, L15, X15) %>%
  ungroup %>% 
  mutate(RS = rowSums(.[,3:8]))

# dff1.1 <- df %>% group_by(TYPE) %>% 
#   summarise_each(funs(mean, sd, n()), Gdl, Odl, Jdl, Ldl, Xdl) %>%
#   #mutate(RS = rowSums(.[,2:7])) %>%
#   select(TYPE, Gloomy.mean = Gdl_mean, Gloomy.sd = Gdl_sd,
#          Oyster.mean = Odl_mean, Oyster.sd = Odl_sd,
#          JapaneseMaple.mean = Jdl_mean, JapaneseMaple.sd = Jdl_sd,
#          Lecanium.mean = Ldl_mean, Lecanium.sd = Ldl_sd, 
#           X.mean = Xdl_mean, X.sd = Xdl_sd, N = Gdl_n)
# 
# dff1.1 <- as.data.frame(dff1.1)

dff11 <- dff1 %>% group_by(YEAR, TYPE) %>% 
  summarize(B = (B15/RS)*100, G = (G15/RS)*100, J = (J15/RS)*100, L = (L15/RS)*100, O = (O15/RS)*100, X = (X15/RS)*100)
target_cols <- names(dff11)[3:8]

dff1z <- dff11 %>% pivot_longer(cols=target_cols, names_to = "Scales", values_to = "Abundance")
# dfz19 <- dff1z %>% filter()
  
ggplot(dff1z, aes(x=TYPE, y = Abundance, fill = Scales)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", color="black") + ylab("Proportional Abundance") + facet_grid(~YEAR) + scale_fill_manual(values=c('#ffffb3','#8dd3c7','#bebada','#fb8072','#80b1d3','#fdb462')) + cowplot::theme_cowplot()

3 Gloomy Scales vs Impervious Surface Cover

Impervious surface is not a robust linear predictor of gloomy scale abundance

3.1 Results from 2018 data

3.1.1 All three red maple types

fit.s.i <- lm(gloom~Imp, data=df19)
#kable(summary(fit.s.i)$coef, digits=2)
# stargazer(fit.s.i, type="html")
# 
# lm(gloom~Imp, data=df19) %>%
#   tidy() %>%
#   mutate(
#     p.value = scales::pvalue(p.value),
#     term = c("Intercept", "% impervious")
#   ) %>%
#   kable(
#     caption = "Estimates for a model fitted to estimate gloomy scale density by impervious surface cover.",
#     col.names = c("Predictor", "Est.", "SE", "t", "p"),
#     digits = c(0, 2, 3, 2, 3),
#     align = c("l", "r", "r", "r", "r")
#   )


tab_model(fit.s.i, show.est=TRUE, show.se = TRUE, show.stat = TRUE, p.style = "a")
  gloom
Predictors Estimates std. Error CI Statistic

my.formula <- y ~ x

ggplot(data = df19, aes(x = Imp, y = gloom)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se=FALSE, color="black", formula = my.formula) +
  stat_poly_eq(formula = my.formula,
               eq.with.lhs = "italic(hat(y))~`=`~",
               aes(label = paste(..eq.label.., ..rr.label.., sep = "*plain(\",\")~")), 
               parse = TRUE) +         
  geom_point() +
  ylab("gloomy scale abundance [log10(x+1)] per 15cm") + xlab("Percent impervious surface") +
  labs(title=paste(TYPE_Names,collapse=", "))

4 Tree Condition vs Impervious Surface

The relationship between impervious surface and tree condition is weak and largely not signficant with these dataset.

Could try binary tree condition.

4.1 Results from 2018

4.1.1 All red maple types

# row_spec(bb2, bold.me2, bold = TRUE, color = "brown", background="cyan")
bb7
YEAR TYPE y.level term estimate std.error statistic p.value Chi2 p.Chi2
2018 Cultivar Good Imp 0.957 0.01 -3.86 0.000 22.38 0
2018 Cultivar Poor Imp 1.002 0.01 0.14 0.885 22.38 0 
ggplot(imp.preds.a19, aes(x = Imp, y = prob, color = Condition, lty=Condition)) + geom_line(size=1.25) + 
  geom_line(size=1.15) + scale_linetype_manual(values = c("solid", "dashed", "dotted")) + 
  ylab("Probability of Given Tree Condition") + xlab("Percent impervious surface") +
  labs(title=paste(TYPE_Names,collapse=", "))
